rawContent:
Beyond the buzz and sensational headlines of the "Magnificent 7". 

The so-called ‘Magnificent 7” which comprises of #Apple (AAPL), #Amazon.com (AMZN), #Alphabet (GOOGL), #Meta Platforms (META), #Microsoft (MSFT), #Nvidia (NVDA), and #Tesla (TSLA) has dominated financial discussions for the past year or so. From social media to television, it seems impossible to escape their influence. And for good reason: they more than doubled in value last year, contributing significantly to the growth of the S&P 500.   

However, the conversation surrounding the "Magnificent 7" has often been one-sided, focusing primarily on their lofty valuations and the concentration risk. Rarely discussed is the often-overlooked aspect of fundamentals. As the chart below illustrates, the "Magnificent 7" are not simply riding on hype; they have demonstrably delivered on fundamental metrics. Whether the growth justifies the valuations is a matter of opinion, but the fact is these companies deserve to trade at a premium of the rest of the market. In fact, the disparities in their expected earnings for Q4 paint an even more intriguing picture.

No one in anyone's patreon should be buying ANYTHING:

Not CELH, Not AAPL, not AMZN, not VZ, not TFC, not commercial RE... we should be discussing how to hedge, not what to buy.  Mag7 are TOTALLY exposed to AI/tech freefall.

So far, we are speculating on the POSSIBILITIES that AI can bring to bear, but we are VERY far from the tech penetrating the stratification of most of the S&P500 companies, let alone the economy as a whole.

Dotcom revolutionized business first, THEN it burst.  Everyone who needed a website had one, and would keep it.  Everyone had built email into their business activities, and kept it.  I expect AI will take a similar form of disruption.
